  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money (dirty money) appear legal (clean) by passing it through complex financial transactions. Key legal elements typically include:\n\n1. Basic legal components:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming illegal proceeds into seemingly legitimate assets\n- Attempting to disguise the origin of criminal proceeds\n\n2. Common legal stages:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (creating complex transactions to obscure origin)\n- Integration (reintroducing funds as seemingly legitimate income)\n\n3. Jurisdictional variations:\n- Different countries have specific statutory definitions\n- Most definitions require intent to hide criminal proceeds\n- Specific monetary thresholds may vary\n\n4. Typical criteria for prosecution:\n- Knowledge of funds' illegal origin\n- Purposeful attempt to disguise funds\n- Engagement in financial transactions designed to conceal source\n\n5. Types of predicate crimes often associated:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Terrorist financing\n- Illegal gambling\n\nThese are general legal principles. Specific definitions can vary by jurisdiction and legal context.",
